nodes.html: Uploading files to an API might seem like a solved problem, and mostly it is, but the trick is selecting the best practice solution for your situation.

nodes.html: This post provides a view of REST API file upload best practice for engineers and managers.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01
Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: We’ll give an overview of the solutions for those that are less technical as well as dive into some of the technical details. This is essential to help engineers and managers understand each other, what is being proposed and how to decide on a solution.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: Let’s establish some context first, what do we mean by a REST API file upload and why does it matter?

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: REST API File Upload: What is It, Why It Matters

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: Before we can get into discussing how to handle file uploads specifically we need to cover off some explanations and background:

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: • APIs are interfaces that define and enable two computer systems to communicate.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01
Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: • REST is a common and highly popular approach to designing and building APIs.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01
Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: • Files come in all different shapes and sizes. They could be a few bytes through to megabytes or gigabytes in size.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01
Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: Going into detail on these is beyond the scope of this post.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: So now, why do we need to discuss file uploads and APIs? There are a few reasons:

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01
Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01
Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: • Compute usage: Given API services usually have some functionality or smarts built in, receiving files usually isn’t the best use of compute power. ‘Dumber’ or fit for purpose file upload and receive services are better suited.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: Now that we’ve covered the context and the problem we can now look at different solutions you can provide for your API.

nodes.html: We’ll then close out by looking at some of the other considerations around files and APIs.

nodes.html: To help work through the solutions let’s establish an example API we can come back to throughout the solutions.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: We need to deliver APIs for a pet insurance company, PetCo. We will mostly focus on PetCo’s Quote API, a fictitious API that we can call to get an insurance quote from PetCo.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: For engineers the endpoint might be: GET api.petco.com/quote

Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: You can embed a file directly into an API call. When the API consumer sends their request for a quote they include the file in the API call itself, so there is just one query.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: In our PetCo Quote API example, if we required a CSV of past medical expenses as part of the quote and we expect it to be fairly small for a pet then there are merits to embedding this in the API call of GET api.petco.com/quote.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: The benefit of this is simplicity. It’s all in one. Easy to understand. Easy to use. Easy to build.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: The downside is you are consuming smarter compute resources doing something simpler, often at a higher cost than purposely designed resources. The other downside is, file processing time slows down responding to your consumer.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: This can be suitable for small file sizes.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: This isn’t suitable where you will have one or more files that start to measure in megabytes.

nodes.html: Link File as URI in API Call

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: You can link to a file within the API call using a URI (essentially a URL like www.site.com/file-123.pdf). The API service then knows to go and fetch the file from the URI specified and can download it in whatever the best way is.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: In our PetCo Quote API example, if we want a photo of the dog as part of the quote then someone developing against the API could make the photo available on a public cloud bucket (e.g. AWS S3 or GCP Storage Bucket). Then just put the link to it in the API call.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: The benefit of this is simplicity for the API provider (PetCo in our example). It also allows you to use appropriate compute resources for downloading the file to where you need it.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01
Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: These downsides make this an unattractive solution in most cases, however it gives us the foundation for some more solution options that we will cover next.

nodes.html: You can build on the Link File solution by providing an upload service to your API consumers.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: The way it would work is this:

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: • Consumer uploads files: API consumer uses your file upload service to upload their file(s) (e.g. PUT files.petco.com/quote/photos)

nodes.html: • Call API: API consumer then calls your API, giving it the links to the files that were uploaded. (e.g. GET api.petco.com/quote)

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01
Element has sufficient color contrast of 5
Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: The API call itself can respond quickly and you’ve made it easy for users to upload files. Compute resources are used effectively. So we’ve overcome some of the challenges with the approaches we’ve already covered.

nodes.html: The challenge with this approach is you’re relying on the user to associate files properly and you are potentially allowing file uploads from people that should not be allowed to do so (which makes various attacks possible, not to mention handling files unnecessarily).

nodes.html: This solution works in the following steps:

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: • Call the API: A consumer calls your API which gives you a token or location as well as authorisation to upload.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01
Element has sufficient color contrast of 7.01

nodes.html: • Upload files: A consumer then uploads the files to or with the appropriate location(s) and token(s) respectively. They also have authorisation to do so.

nodes.html: To continue the PetCo Quote example, here is how we would do a quote with a photo of the dog as well as the CSV with past expenses. Let’s step through it:

nodes.html: • An API consumer could call the Quote API to get a quote (e.g. GET api.petco.com/quote)

nodes.html: • The Get Quote API would respond quickly with a quote identifier or token to use.

nodes.html:
• The API consumer then calls Get Quote File Upload Service, specifying the quote identifier and file type.
    e.g. PUT files.petco.com/quote/{quote-id}/photos

nodes.html: • After some time authorisation to upload is revoked from this API consumer.

nodes.html: The API call itself can respond quickly and compute resources are used most effectively. You can also control data processing.

nodes.html: The downside is relatively minor in that you’ve introduced an extra step. So it’s not as simple as embedding the file. However, this extra step outweighs the downsides of embedding, even with smaller files.
